HEADWORD: Salpa
<hw>Sal"pa</hw> <pr>(s⟦acr⟧l"p⟦adot⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> L. <plw>Salpae</plw> <pr>(s⟦acr⟧l"p⟦emac⟧)</pr>, E.
<plw>Salpas</plw> <pr>(s⟦acr⟧l"p⟦adot⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL.: cf. L.
<ets>salpa</ets> a kind of stockfish.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A
genus of transparent, tubular, free-swimming oceanic tunicates found
abundantly in all the warmer latitudes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Each species exists in two distinct forms, one of which
lives solitary, and produces, by budding from an internal organ, a
series of the other kind. These are united together, side by side, so as
to form a chain, or cluster, often of large size. Each of the
individuals composing the chain carries a single egg, which develops
into the solitary kind.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Salpid</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Salpian</ent>⟦br⟧
